## Summary

**Classification: runtime bug fix — silent mid-call failure that strands live calls (dead air) and leaks per-call resources.**

After the OpenAI Realtime handshake, `connectOpenAIRealtime` never listens for `error` or `close` again (`src/openai.ts`): the only error listener is the handshake's `ws.once("error", reject)`, which after a successful open just dangles on a settled promise. Two consequences:

1. **Dead-air calls.** If OpenAI drops the WebSocket mid-call (network blip, server-side session teardown, idle timeout), the bridge never finds out. The Twilio leg stays up, the caller sits in silence indefinitely, nothing is written to `events.jsonl`, and the agent client (potentially a subprocess) and logger leak until Twilio eventually gives up. `ws` 8.x makes this fully silent: `send()` on a closed socket is a buffered no-op, so even continued caller audio produces no signal that the session is gone.
2. **A latent crash window.** The stale handshake listener swallows the *first* mid-call `error` event (reject on a settled promise) and is then removed — a subsequent `error` on that socket would be unlistened and take down the whole process, every concurrent call included.

### The fix

- `src/openai.ts`: on open, detach the handshake reject listener and attach a persistent `error` recorder (no socket error can ever be unlistened again) plus a `close` listener. The client gains `onClose(handler)` — close info is buffered if it arrives before registration, mirroring the existing buffered-server-events pattern.
- `src/server.ts`: the bridge registers `onClose` — it logs `openai.ws.closed` (with code/reason), runs the existing idempotent `cleanupCall()`, and closes the Twilio socket so the caller gets a clean call end instead of dead air. Self-initiated closes during normal teardown are ignored via the existing `closed` guard, so no double-cleanup.
- `src/config.ts`: new optional `OPENAI_REALTIME_URL` override for the realtime endpoint (gateways, self-hosted relays — and what makes the live behavior proof below reproducible by anyone without burning provider credentials). Defaults to the existing hardcoded endpoint; no behavior change unless set.

Verified against the actual library behavior before scoping: `@fastify/websocket` 11.x already guards the Twilio socket's `error` event (index.js:130), so the Twilio leg needs no change — the fix stays confined to the OpenAI leg.

## Real behavior proof — live two-call run against a running `vox serve` process

Per review guidance, here is redacted runtime evidence from an owned test-call setup: the **actual `vox serve` CLI process** (real Fastify server, real `connectOpenAIRealtime`, real per-call logger and playback tracking), a **real WebSocket caller speaking the Twilio Media Streams protocol** (`connected`/`start`/20 ms μ-law `media` frames), and a **real WebSocket realtime provider** that completes the session handshake, streams assistant audio, then **destroys the TCP socket mid-call without a close frame**. The only substitution is the provider endpoint itself (via `OPENAI_REALTIME_URL`, since neither OpenAI nor Twilio can be made to drop a live connection on demand); every process, socket, and code path in between is production.

```
$ OPENAI_API_KEY=<redacted> OPENAI_REALTIME_URL=ws://127.0.0.1:8081 \
  VOX_PUBLIC_BASE_URL=https://<redacted>.example.com VOX_LOG_DIR=/tmp/vox-demo/logs \
  node --import tsx src/cli.ts serve --port 3100
vox serve listening on http://127.0.0.1:3100
```

Caller output — the disconnect ends the caller leg in **2 ms**, exactly one close, and the same server process immediately handles a second healthy call:

```
2026-06-12T16:13:07.941Z call 1 (provider dies mid-call): connected to /twilio
2026-06-12T16:13:11.949Z call 1 (provider dies mid-call): socket closed (code=1005) after 4008ms —
                         191 caller media frames sent, 1 assistant media + 1 marks received
---
2026-06-12T16:13:11.951Z call 2 (same server process, caller hangs up normally): connected to /twilio
2026-06-12T16:13:14.453Z call 2 (...): socket closed (code=1005) after 2502ms —
                         119 caller media frames sent, 1 assistant media + 1 marks received
2026-06-12T16:13:14.486Z GET /health after both calls -> {"ok":true}
```

Provider log pinning the kill timestamp (16:13:11.947) against the caller-side close (16:13:11.949):

```
2026-06-12T16:13:07.945Z provider: vox connected (call 1)
2026-06-12T16:13:07.947Z provider: session 1 configured (input audio/pcmu)
2026-06-12T16:13:11.947Z provider: !!! destroying TCP socket for call 1 mid-call (no close frame) !!!
2026-06-12T16:13:11.952Z provider: vox connected (call 2)
```

Call 1's `events.jsonl` — the disconnect is recorded with the real close code, and it is the **final line** of the log (completed cleanup, no late writes):

```
{"t":"2026-06-12T16:13:07.941Z","source":"vox","payload":{"type":"twilio.ws.connected"}}
{"t":"2026-06-12T16:13:07.946Z","source":"vox","payload":{"type":"twilio.start","streamSid":"MZ_demo_1","callSid":"CA_MZ_demo_1"}}
{"t":"2026-06-12T16:13:07.947Z","source":"openai","payload":{"type":"session.updated", ...}}
{"t":"2026-06-12T16:13:11.948Z","source":"vox","payload":{"type":"openai.ws.closed","code":1006,"reason":""}}
```

Call 2's `events.jsonl` shows a normal full lifecycle through the same process (`twilio.ws.connected` → `twilio.start` → `session.updated` → `twilio.stop`). On unfixed main the same scenario leaves call 1's socket open indefinitely (the caller keeps streaming into dead air), logs nothing, and never cleans up — the mechanism is pinned fail-before by the committed regression test below.

<details>
<summary>Reproduce it yourself: the two harness scripts (run with the repo's installed <code>ws</code>)</summary>

`provider.mjs` — realtime stand-in that handshakes, streams audio, then destroys the TCP socket:

```js
import { createRequire } from "node:module";
const require = createRequire(`${process.cwd()}/package.json`);
const { WebSocketServer } = require("ws");
const ts = () => new Date().toISOString();
const wss = new WebSocketServer({ host: "127.0.0.1", port: 8081 });
let calls = 0;
wss.on("connection", (ws) => {
  const call = ++calls;
  console.log(`${ts()} provider: vox connected (call ${call})`);
  ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: "session.created", session: { id: `sess_demo_${call}` } }));
  ws.on("message", (data) => {
    const evt = JSON.parse(data.toString());
    if (evt.type === "session.update") {
      ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: "session.updated", session: evt.session }));
      console.log(`${ts()} provider: session ${call} configured (input ${evt.session?.audio?.input?.format?.type})`);
      setTimeout(() => ws.send(JSON.stringify({
        type: "response.output_audio.delta", item_id: `item_demo_${call}`,
        delta: Buffer.alloc(8000, 0xff).toString("base64"),
      })), 1000);
    }
  });
  ws.on("error", () => {});
  if (call === 1) setTimeout(() => {
    console.log(`${ts()} provider: !!! destroying TCP socket for call 1 mid-call (no close frame) !!!`);
    ws._socket.destroy();
  }, 4000);
});
console.log(`${ts()} provider: realtime stand-in listening on ws://127.0.0.1:8081`);
```

`caller.mjs` — Twilio Media Streams protocol client (two calls + health check):

```js
import { createRequire } from "node:module";
const require = createRequire(`${process.cwd()}/package.json`);
const WebSocket = require("ws");
const ts = () => new Date().toISOString();
const SILENCE_20MS = Buffer.alloc(160, 0xff).toString("base64");
function call(label, streamSid, { hangupAfterMs = null } = {}) {
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    const ws = new WebSocket("ws://127.0.0.1:3100/twilio");
    let media = null, t0 = null, framesSent = 0, mediaReceived = 0, marksReceived = 0;
    ws.on("open", () => {
      t0 = Date.now();
      console.log(`${ts()} ${label}: connected to /twilio`);
      ws.send(JSON.stringify({ event: "connected", protocol: "Call", version: "1.0.0" }));
      ws.send(JSON.stringify({ event: "start", sequenceNumber: "1", streamSid, start: {
        streamSid, callSid: `CA_${streamSid}`, accountSid: "AC_demo",
        mediaFormat: { encoding: "audio/x-mulaw", sampleRate: 8000, channels: 1 } } }));
      media = setInterval(() => ws.send(JSON.stringify({ event: "media", streamSid,
        media: { track: "inbound", timestamp: String(++framesSent * 20), payload: SILENCE_20MS } })), 20);
      if (hangupAfterMs) setTimeout(() => { ws.send(JSON.stringify({ event: "stop", streamSid })); ws.close(); }, hangupAfterMs);
    });
    ws.on("message", (data) => {
      const evt = JSON.parse(data.toString());
      if (evt.event === "media") mediaReceived += 1;
      if (evt.event === "mark") marksReceived += 1;
    });
    ws.on("close", (code) => {
      clearInterval(media);
      console.log(`${ts()} ${label}: socket closed (code=${code}) after ${Date.now() - t0}ms — ` +
        `${framesSent} caller media frames sent, ${mediaReceived} assistant media + ${marksReceived} marks received`);
      resolve(undefined);
    });
    ws.on("error", (e) => console.log(`${ts()} ${label}: error ${e.message}`));
  });
}
await call("call 1 (provider dies mid-call)", "MZ_demo_1");
console.log("---");
await call("call 2 (same server process, caller hangs up normally)", "MZ_demo_2", { hangupAfterMs: 2500 });
console.log(`${ts()} GET /health after both calls ->`, JSON.stringify(await fetch("http://127.0.0.1:3100/health").then((r) => r.json())));
```

Run: `node provider.mjs` → start `vox serve` with the env shown above → `node caller.mjs`.

</details>

## Reproducibility — deterministic, real sockets

Two committed layers:

**`test/openai.test.ts`** exercises the **real client over real WebSocket connections** to a local `WebSocketServer` (no fakes on the transport under test): server-initiated close reaches the handler with code/reason; a close landing before registration is buffered, not lost; an abrupt TCP `terminate()` (no close frame) surfaces as `onClose` with 1006 instead of an unhandled `error`; `send()` after the drop is a no-op.

**`test/server-openai-disconnect.test.ts`** drives the real `handleTwilioSocket` through the production sequence (start → session.created → session.updated → connection close) and pins the contract: the disconnect is logged, the Twilio socket is closed exactly once, cleanup runs exactly once, late traffic is ignored, and an OpenAI close *after* Twilio-initiated teardown is a no-op (no re-close, no late log writes).

Against the unfixed code (`git checkout origin/main -- src/openai.ts src/server.ts`):

```
$ node --import tsx --test test/server-openai-disconnect.test.ts
not ok 1 - mid-call OpenAI disconnect tears the call down instead of leaving dead air
  failureType: 'testCodeFailure'
  error: 'the disconnect must be visible in the call log'
  name: 'AssertionError'
# tests 2
# pass 1
# fail 1
```

— the bridge observably does nothing when the session dies: no log entry, Twilio socket never closed, no cleanup. With the fix, all new tests pass.

